## FileTree Component

The `FileTree` component is a React component designed to render a hierarchical file and folder structure. It allows users to navigate through a nested list of nodes, expand and collapse folders, and select individual files.

### Purpose

This component is used to visualize and interact with a tree-like representation of files and directories, commonly found in file explorers or documentation navigation panels.

### Props

*   `nodes`: An array of `TreeNode` objects, representing the root level of the tree. Each `TreeNode` can be either a `FolderNode` or a `FileNode`.
*   `activeKey`: The `key` of the currently selected file node. If `null`, no file is considered active.
*   `activeFolderPath`: The `path` of the currently active folder. This is used to visually highlight the active folder.
*   `onSelect`: A callback function that is invoked when a file node is clicked. It receives the `key` of the selected file.
*   `onFolder`: A callback function that is invoked when a folder node is clicked. It receives the `path` of the clicked folder.
*   `depth`: (Internal use) The current depth of the node in the tree, used for indentation. Defaults to 0.
*   `pathPrefix`: (Internal use) A prefix string used to construct the full path for nested folders. Defaults to an empty string.

### Components

*   **`FileTree`**: The main component that recursively renders the tree structure.
*   **`FolderRow`**: Renders a single folder row, including its name, an expand/collapse toggle (chevron), and an icon. It also recursively renders its children using the `FileTree` component.
*   **`FileRow`**: Renders a single file row, including its name and an icon. It handles click events to select the file.
*   **`FolderIcon`**: An SVG component to display a folder icon, which changes appearance based on whether the folder is open or closed.
*   **`FileIcon`**: An SVG component to display a file icon.

### Usage Example

```tsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { FileTree, TreeNode } from './FileTree'; // Assuming FileTree is exported from this file

const sampleNodes: TreeNode[] = [
  {
    kind: 'folder',
    name: 'src',
    children: [
      {
        kind: 'folder',
        name: 'lib',
        children: [
          { kind: 'file', name: 'tree.ts', key: 'src/lib/tree.ts', title: 'Tree utilities' },
        ],
      },
      { kind: 'file', name: 'App.tsx', key: 'src/App.tsx', title: 'Main application component' },
    ],
  },
  {
    kind: 'folder',
    name: 'public',
    children: [
      { kind: 'file', name: 'index.html', key: 'public/index.html', title: 'Public index page' },
    ],
  },
  { kind: 'file', name: 'package.json', key: 'package.json', title: 'Project dependencies' },
];

function App() {
  const [activeKey, setActiveKey] = useState<string | null>(null);
  const [activeFolderPath, setActiveFolderPath] = useState<string | null>(null);

  const handleSelectFile = (key: string) => {
    setActiveKey(key);
    setActiveFolderPath(null); // Deselect folder when a file is selected
  };

  const handleSelectFolder = (path: string) => {
    setActiveFolderPath(path);
    setActiveKey(null); // Deselect file when a folder is selected
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <FileTree
        nodes={sampleNodes}
        activeKey={activeKey}
        activeFolderPath={activeFolderPath}
        onSelect={handleSelectFile}
        onFolder={handleSelectFolder}
      />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

This example demonstrates how to use the `FileTree` component with sample data, managing the active file and folder states using React's `useState` hook.
